caption: Table 1: Fraction of children with siblings. This table presents the proportion of children with siblings, along with the total number of children in each dataset.
description: This table shows the percentage of children with siblings and the total number of children for six different daycare datasets from three municipalities in Japan.  The data is broken down by municipality and year, offering a snapshot of sibling prevalence in real-world daycare markets.

caption: Table 2: Average length of preferences. The second column pertains to families with only one child, while the third column represents families with siblings. The last column displays the average number of distinct daycares in the corresponding individual preference lists for children with siblings.
description: This table presents statistics on the length of preference lists for children in daycare matching markets.  It breaks down the average number of daycare centers listed in preference orderings by family type (only child vs. sibling) and provides the average number of unique daycares listed for children with siblings.  These statistics highlight differences in preference expression between children from single-child families and those from families with multiple children.

caption: Table 3: Number of families with siblings and twins. The second and third columns represent families with 2 children, while the last two columns represent families with 3 or more children.
description: This table presents a breakdown of the number of families with siblings in six real-life datasets from three municipalities.  It distinguishes between families with two children and those with three or more children, further categorizing them by whether the children are twins.  The data provides insight into family structures in these daycare markets.

caption: Table 4: Demand and supply by age
description: This table shows the number of applicants and available slots (capacity) in daycare centers categorized by the age group of the children (0-5 years old) across six different real-life datasets from three municipalities (Shibuya, Tama, and Koriyama).  It highlights the significant imbalance in demand and supply across different age groups, particularly a shortage of slots for children aged 0 and 1, and a surplus of slots for children aged 4 and 5. This imbalance is a key characteristic of the practical daycare markets investigated in the paper.

caption: Table 5: Results of computation times (seconds) for experiments on real-world data.
description: This table presents the computational times, in seconds, for both the ESDA and CP algorithms, for the six real-life datasets.  The ESDA algorithm consistently demonstrates significantly faster performance than the CP algorithm across all datasets.
